1
00:00:00,402 --> 00:00:18,478
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:19,015 --> 00:00:33,006
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sammasambuddhasam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:45,198 --> 00:00:48,920
We were doing all the words to do with the

4
00:00:49,659 --> 00:00:53,256
paticca-samuppada, dependent origination.

5
00:00:53,597 --> 00:00:56,811
Some people translate that, remember, as interdependent origination.

6
00:00:57,996 --> 00:00:59,281
And we've been through the

7
00:01:00,088 --> 00:01:28,475
avijjā, the words we did was avijjā, saṅkāra, viṇyāna, nāma-rupa, salayatana, passo, vedana, tanha, upadāna and bhāva and they translate or are translated as ignorance, intentional activities or volitional conditionings consciousness, mind and matter

8
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:40,382
Six-fold sense base, contact, feeling, craving, grasping and becoming.

9
00:01:42,266 --> 00:01:49,620
And then we're going through just the last bit which is Bhāvapācchā jñāti.

10
00:01:50,106 --> 00:02:01,567
So there, in a sense, it's a bit of a repetition because

11
00:02:03,033 --> 00:02:12,044
The Bhāva, the becoming, is then described as the jhāti, jhāra and māraṇā, so birth, ageing and death.

12
00:02:12,064 --> 00:02:17,292
Jhāti, birth, jhāra, ageing, māraṇā and death.

13
00:02:17,312 --> 00:02:24,441
And the rest of it, saukhā, parideva, dukkha, dhammanāsa, really all the Buddha is saying that this leads to the whole gamut of human suffering.

14
00:02:25,962 --> 00:02:32,431
It translates as sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief and despair.

15
00:02:32,412 --> 00:02:35,877
So people have tried to make some sense out of the order of that, but it's not.

16
00:02:35,917 --> 00:02:45,651
I think he's just saying, look, when you behave like this, basically you're creating misery, and that's about it.

17
00:02:46,572 --> 00:02:56,866
Now, what we have to do this evening is just recognize that there are two interpretations to this particular teaching, dependent origination.

18
00:02:57,348 --> 00:03:00,832
The traditional one is to do with three lives.

19
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:14,525
So when we are born, we come into this life with the first two parts, the avijja, which is your basic ignorance, your basic delusion, and all the conditioning that you've gained from your previous lives.

20
00:03:16,127 --> 00:03:20,155
And remember that, really, that's your karma.

21
00:03:20,522 --> 00:03:31,985
So the mental states, the potential mental states that you're born with, the seeds that are already there within consciousness, within the mind, are your karma.

22
00:03:32,006 --> 00:03:35,231
That's what you're born with into this present life.

23
00:03:35,413 --> 00:03:36,675
This is the three life theory.

24
00:03:38,848 --> 00:03:42,653
And then you pass through this life, turning this wheel.

25
00:03:42,674 --> 00:03:44,477
And remember, we're not always turning the wheel.

26
00:03:44,556 --> 00:03:47,941
When we're asleep, there's no paticca-samuppada.

27
00:03:47,961 --> 00:03:50,544
And so it's not as though it's always there.

28
00:03:50,625 --> 00:03:59,417
But every time there's an act of volition, which is based on greed, hatred, or this essential delusion, then the wheel turns.

29
00:03:59,717 --> 00:04:02,881
And what it's doing is, it's reinforcing conditioning.

30
00:04:03,461 --> 00:04:05,585
And you may even be starting some new stuff.

31
00:04:06,145 --> 00:04:07,067
Why not?

32
00:04:07,046 --> 00:04:07,769
Well, we're at it.

33
00:04:08,149 --> 00:04:11,637
If we're going to create misery, we may as well get in there and have a good go.

34
00:04:13,540 --> 00:04:22,781
And this leads us to this bhāva, which just means this continuous becoming, translated also as samsara, the world of ever going on, no end to it.

35
00:04:25,086 --> 00:04:26,389
And then when we die,

36
00:04:26,976 --> 00:04:32,122
Then that process of being born, growing old and dying starts again.

37
00:04:32,163 --> 00:04:39,129
So the last bit in a future life is really saying that this wheel of dependent origination is just going to keep going, just going to keep going.

38
00:04:41,392 --> 00:04:47,079
So those are your three life theory, which is your traditional one.

39
00:04:47,119 --> 00:04:55,767
That's the one you'll get from Buddhaghosa in his book, The Path of Purification.

40
00:05:05,569 --> 00:05:18,435
And in that particular teaching, the vijnana that they're talking about right at the beginning there, that consciousness that we were relating to, is the relinking consciousness which moves from one life to the next.

41
00:05:18,875 --> 00:05:22,583
So it's an actually specific definition of that vijnana.

42
00:05:24,064 --> 00:05:37,738
But as we mentioned before, there's also a present moment understanding of this teaching in which the avijja-saṅkāra is the platform upon which every moment is sitting.

43
00:05:38,199 --> 00:05:48,250
It's sitting on the delusion, this misunderstanding, and all the saṅkāras, all these volitional conditionings,

44
00:05:48,483 --> 00:06:13,156
as conditionings ready to be activated given the right stimulus so they're often referred to as those conditionings, the set conditionings they lie there as potential then with every moment there arises the potential again of some action

45
00:06:13,271 --> 00:06:20,079
And if it's arising out of this base, if it's arising out of that base, then you get this turning of dependent origination.

46
00:06:21,401 --> 00:06:33,677
In which case, the jati jara-maranam is referring back onto this present moment, that each moment has a beginning to it, it has a process to it, and it has an end to it.

47
00:06:35,007 --> 00:06:57,875
so the wheel as it were, these three wheels are turning within themselves so there's this basic wheel of delusion feeding into the conditioning as a potential then there's this active feed down into this already present potential conditioning of the actions we are doing

48
00:06:58,834 --> 00:07:03,600
and this produces, in every moment, a beginning, a middle and an end.

49
00:07:04,300 --> 00:07:11,269
And that's, in short, the understanding of paticca-sampada as a present moment experience.

50
00:07:12,391 --> 00:07:17,857
So it's up to you, really, which one you put the accent on.

51
00:07:18,478 --> 00:07:25,685
In terms of traditional teachings, they would emphasize the three lives.

52
00:07:26,307 --> 00:07:37,661
But in terms of our practice, our daily practice, and what we're trying to do is escape this wheel, then I think it makes more sense to see it as a moment-to-moment experience.

53
00:07:38,624 --> 00:07:47,815
But that's not to deny the three-life theory, because, of course, when we do die, all those conditionings are carried over onto the next life.

54
00:07:50,259 --> 00:07:52,382
And that's really where our karma is.

55
00:07:53,593 --> 00:08:04,327
Often we think of karma as something coming at us from the outside, but actually it's the inner part of ourselves because that's where we experience suffering.

56
00:08:04,887 --> 00:08:12,177
Just because somebody shouts at you, you stupid bald-headed monk, heaven forbid, then heaven forgive them.

57
00:08:15,120 --> 00:08:20,427
Just because somebody shouts at you doesn't mean that it hurts you, you know, sticks and stones hurt my bones and all that.

58
00:08:20,964 --> 00:08:25,396
But how we react to that is our suffering, our karma.

59
00:08:25,997 --> 00:08:33,294
And the whole of the Buddhist teaching, as far as I can see, is about putting an end to this dependent origination.

60
00:08:33,735 --> 00:08:34,577
That's your samsara.

61
00:08:35,240 --> 00:08:38,147
All the teachings are about trying to bring that to an end.

62
00:08:38,379 --> 00:09:03,341
undercutting it and remember that the undercutting has these two sides first of all through action so by constantly noting our intentions letting go of those that are undermining us unwholesome leading to more suffering and reinforcing those that are not that are actually leading to virtue there is that active change

63
00:09:03,524 --> 00:09:12,480
But underneath that there has to be this vipassana which is cutting into the basic delusion which is creating the whole problem.

64
00:09:13,864 --> 00:09:20,556
So remember the growth of wisdom and the growth of virtue must run concurrent in the spiritual life.

65
00:09:20,636 --> 00:09:23,000
You can't have the one without the other.

66
00:09:25,580 --> 00:09:36,452
And that, I think, brings to an end my small dharma bites, my little discussions on the dependent origination, paticca samavada.

67
00:09:37,214 --> 00:09:39,777
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

68
00:09:40,498 --> 00:09:53,494
May you be liberated sooner rather than later.

